# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: com-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:com-automation/activex] ActiveX is still supported in the "Internet Explorer mode" of Microsoft Edge (which has a different, incompatible extension system, as it is based on Google's Chromium project).
[src:com-automation/activex] ActiveX was one of the major technologies used in component-based software engineering.
[src:com-automation/activex] Compared with JavaBeans, ActiveX supports more programming languages, but JavaBeans supports more platforms.
[src:com-automation/activex] ActiveX is supported in many rapid application development technologies, such as Active Template Library, Delphi, JavaBeans, Microsoft Foundation Class Library, Qt, Visual Basic, Windows Forms and wxWidgets, to enable application developers to embed ActiveX controls into their products.
[src:com-automation/activex] Internet Explorer also allows the embedding of ActiveX controls in web pages.
[src:com-automation/activex] Faced with the complexity of OLE 2.0 and with poor support for COM in MFC, Microsoft simplified the specification and rebranded the technology as ActiveX in 1996.
[src:com-automation/activex] Even after simplification, users still required controls to implement about six core interfaces.
[src:com-automation/activex] In response to this complexity, Microsoft produced wizards, ATL base classes, macros and C++ language extensions to make it simpler to write controls.
[src:com-automation/activex] Starting with Internet Explorer 3.0 (1996), Microsoft added support to host ActiveX controls within HTML content.
[src:com-automation/activex] Microsoft subsequently introduced security measures to make browsing including ActiveX safer.
[src:com-automation/activex] ActiveX was controversial from the start; while Microsoft claimed programming ease and good performance compared to Java applets in its marketing materials, critics of ActiveX were quick to point out security issues and lack of portability, making it impractical for use outside protected intranets.
[src:com-automation/activex] The ActiveX security model relied almost entirely on identifying trusted component developers using a code signing technology called Authenticode.
[src:com-automation/activex] Developers had to register with Verisign (US$20 per year for individuals, $400 for corporations) and sign a contract, promising not to develop malware.
[src:com-automation/activex] Identified code would then run inside the web browser with full permissions, meaning that any bug in the code was a potential security issue; this contrasts with the sandboxing already used in Java at the time.
[src:com-automation/activex] In October 1996, Microsoft released a beta version of the ActiveX Software Development Kit (SDK) for the Macintosh, including a plug-in for Netscape Navigator on the Mac, and announced its plan to support ActiveX on Solaris later that year.
[src:com-automation/activex] Six months and two more beta releases later, there had yet to be any commercially available Macintosh ActiveX plugins.
[src:com-automation/activex] In 1997, NCompass Labs in cooperation with Microsoft released a plug-in for Netscape Navigator to support ActiveX.
[src:com-automation/activex] Documentation for ActiveX core technology resides at The Open Group and may be read for free.
[src:com-automation/activex] Despite Microsoft's previous efforts to make ActiveX cross-platform, most ActiveX controls would not and will not work on all platforms, so using ActiveX controls to implement essential functionality of a web page restricts its usefulness.
[src:com-automation/activex] The government of South Korea, in a software-agnostic gravitating move, started in circa 2015 to remove the technology from their public websites in order to make their website accessible to more platforms.
[src:com-automation/activex] Microsoft dropped ActiveX support from the Windows Store edition of Internet Explorer 10 in Windows 8.
[src:com-automation/activex] In 2015, Microsoft released Microsoft Edge [Legacy], the replacement for Internet Explorer, with no support for ActiveX; this event marked the end of ActiveX technology in Microsoft's web browser development.
[src:com-automation/activex] Microsoft [New] Edge, however, includes an "Internet Explorer mode" feature, which supports ActiveX.
[src:com-automation/activex] Microsoft has developed a large number of products and software platforms using ActiveX objects.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is the basis for other Microsoft domain-specific component technologies including OLE, OLE Automation, ActiveX, COM+, and DCOM as well as implementations such as DirectX, Windows shell, UMDF, Windows Runtime, and Browser Helper Object.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM enables object use when only the object's interface is known, not its internal implementation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The component implementer defines interfaces that are separate from the implementation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Support for multiple programming contexts is handled by relying on the object for aspects that would be challenging to implement as a facility.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Supporting multiple uses of an object is handled by requiring each object to destroy itself via reference-counting.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Access to an object's interfaces (similar to Type conversion) is provided by each object as well.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is available only in Microsoft Windows and Apple's Core Foundation 1.3 and later plug-in application programming interface (API).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The latter only implements a subset of the whole COM interface.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Over time, COM is being replaced with other technologies such as Microsoft .NET and web services (i.e. via WCF).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] However, COM objects can be used in a .NET language via COM Interop.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is similar to other component technologies such as SOM, CORBA and Enterprise JavaBeans, although each has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Unlike C++, COM provides a stable application binary interface (ABI) that is unaffected by compiler differences.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This makes using COM advantageous for object-oriented C++ libraries that are to be used by clients compiled via different compilers.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Introduced in 1987, Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE) was one of the first interprocess communication technologies in Windows.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] It allowed sending and receiving messages in so-called *conversations* between applications.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] These provided the foundation of many of the ideas behind COM.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Object Linking and Embedding (OLE), Microsoft's first object-based framework, was built on DDE and designed specifically for compound documents.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] It was introduced with Word and Excel in 1991, and was later included with Windows, starting with version 3.1 in 1992.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An example of a compound document is a spreadsheet embedded in a Word document.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] As changes are made to the spreadsheet in Excel, they appear automatically in the Word document.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In 1991, Microsoft introduced the Visual Basic Extension (VBX) technology with Visual Basic 1.0.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A VBX is a packaged extension in the form of a dynamic-link library (DLL) that allows objects to be graphically placed in a form and manipulated by properties and methods.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] These were later adapted for use by other languages such as Visual C++.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In 1992, Microsoft released OLE 2 with its new underlying object model, COM.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The COM application binary interface (ABI) was the same as the MAPI ABI (released in 1992), and like it was based on MSRPC and ultimately on the Open Group's DCE/RPC.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM was created to replace DDE since its text-based conversation and Windows messaging design was not flexible enough to allow sharing application features in a robust and extensible way.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In 1994, the OLE custom control (OCX) technology, based on COM, was introduced as the successor to VBX.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] At the same time, Microsoft stated that OLE 2 would be known simply as "OLE".
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Windows NT 3.5 and Windows 95 integrated OLE 2.0.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In early 1996, Microsoft found a new use for OCX – extending their web browser's capability.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Microsoft renamed some parts of OLE relating to the Internet as ActiveX, and gradually renamed all OLE technologies to ActiveX, except the compound document technology that was used in Microsoft Office.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Later in 1996, Microsoft extended COM to work across the network with DCOM.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In 1997, Windows CE integrated support for COM.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The COM IDL is based on the feature-rich DCE/RPC IDL, with object-oriented extensions.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Microsoft's implementation of DCE/RPC, **MSRPC**, is used as the primary inter-process communication mechanism for Windows NT services and internal components, making it an obvious choice of foundation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] DCOM extends COM from merely supporting a single user with separate applications communicating on the Windows desktop, to activating objects running under different security contexts, and on different machines across the network.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] With this were added necessary features for configuring which users have authority to create, activate and call objects, for identifying the calling user, as well as specifying required encryption for security of calls.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Renamed to **COM+** in Windows 2000, the feature set was incorporated into the operating system as opposed to the series of external tools provided by MTS.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] At the same time, Microsoft de-emphasized DCOM as a separate entity.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Components that used COM+ were handled more directly by the added layer of COM+, in particular by operating system support for interception.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In the first release of MTS, interception was tacked on – installing an MTS component would modify the Windows Registry to call the MTS software, and not the component directly.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Windows 2000 included Component Services control panel updates for configuring COM+ components.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An advantage of COM+ was that it could be run in "component farms".
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Instances of a component, if coded properly, could be pooled and reused by new calls to its initializing routine without unloading it from memory.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Components could also be distributed (called from another machine).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM+ and Microsoft Visual Studio provided tools to make it easy to generate client-side proxies, so although DCOM was used to make the remote call, it was easy to do for developers.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM+ also introduced a subscriber/publisher event mechanism called **COM+ Events**, and provided a new way of leveraging MSMQ (a technology that provides inter-application asynchronous messaging) with components called **Queued Components**.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM+ events extend the COM+ programming model to support late-bound (see Late binding) events or method calls between the publisher or subscriber and the event system.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] .NET provides wrappers to commonly used COM controls.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] .NET can leverage COM+ via the `System.EnterpriseServices` namespace, and several of the services that COM+ provides have been duplicated in .NET.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] For example, the `System.Transactions` namespace provides the `TransactionScope` class, which provides transaction management without resorting to COM+.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Similarly, queued components can be replaced by Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) with an MSMQ transport.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] There is limited support for backward compatibility.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM object may be used in .NET by implementing a Runtime Callable Wrapper (RCW).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] NET objects that conform to certain interface restrictions may be used in COM objects by calling a *COM callable wrapper* (CCW).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] From both the COM and .NET sides, objects using the other technology appear as native objects.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] WCF eases a number of COM's remote execution challenges.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] For instance, it allows objects to be transparently marshalled by value across process or machine boundaries more easily.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Some implementations of Nano-COM such as Direct3D eschew the allocator functions and restrict themselves to only use caller-allocated buffers.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Nano-COM has no notion of classes, apartments, marshaling, registration, etc.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Rather, object references are simply passed across function boundaries and allocated via standard language constructs (e.g., C++ `new` operator).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Nano-COM is currently in use as the base ABI technology for DirectX/Direct3D/DirectML.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Since an ActiveX control (any COM component) runs as native code, with no sandboxing protection, there are few restrictions on what it can do.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Using ActiveX components, as Internet Explorer supported, in a web page lead to problems with malware infections.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Microsoft recognized the problem as far back as 1996 when Charles Fitzgerald said, "We never made the claim up front that ActiveX is intrinsically secure".
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Later versions of Internet Explorer prompt the user before installing an ActiveX control, allowing them to block installation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] As a level of protection, an ActiveX control is signed with a digital signature to guarantee authenticity.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] It is also possible to disable ActiveX controls altogether, or to allow only a selected few.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The transparent support for out-of-process COM servers promotes software safety in terms of process isolation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This can be useful for decoupling subsystems of large application into separate processes.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Process isolation limits state corruption in one process from negatively affecting the integrity of the other processes, since they only communicate through strictly defined interfaces.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Thus, only the affected subsystem needs to be restarted in order to regain valid state.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This is not the case for subsystems within the same process, where a *rogue pointer* in one subsystem can randomly corrupt other subsystems.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is supported via bindings in several languages, such as C, C++, Visual Basic, Delphi, Python and several of the Windows scripting contexts.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Component access is via interface methods.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This allows for direct calling in-process and via the COM/DCOM sub-system access between processes and computers.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A **coclass**, a COM class, implements one or more interfaces.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] It is identified by a class ID, called CLSID which is GUID, and by a human-readable programmatic identifier, called ProgID.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A coclass is created via one of these identifiers.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Each COM **interface** extends the `IUnknown` interface, which exposes methods for reference counting and for accessing the other interfaces of the object – similar to type conversion, a.k.a. type casting.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An interface is identified by an interface ID (IID), a GUID.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A **custom interface**, anything derived from `IUnknown`, provides early bound access via a pointer to a virtual method table that contains a list of pointers to the functions that implement the functions declared in the interface, in the order they are declared.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An in-process invocation overhead is, therefore, comparable to a C++ virtual method call.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Dispatching, a.k.a. late bound access, is provided by implementing `IDispatch`.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Dispatching allows access from a wider range of programming contexts than a custom interface.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Like many object-oriented languages, COM provides a separation of interface from implementation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This distinction is especially strong in COM where an object has no default interface.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A client must request an interface to have any access.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM supports multiple implementations of the same interface, so that clients can choose which implementation of an interface to use.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM **type library** defines COM metadata, such as coclasses and interfaces.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A library can be defined as Interface definition language (IDL); a programming language independent syntax.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] IDL is similar to C++ with additional syntax for defining interfaces and coclasses.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] IDL also supports bracketed attributes before declarations to define metadata such as identifiers and relationships between parameters.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An IDL file is compiled via the MIDL compiler.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] For use with C/C++, the MIDL compiler generates a header file with `struct` definitions to match the vtbls of the declared interfaces and a C file containing declarations of the interface GUIDs.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] C++ source code for a proxy module can also be generated by the MIDL compiler.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This proxy contains method stubs for converting COM calls into remote procedure calls to enable DCOM for out-of-process communication.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] MIDL can generate a binary type library (TLB) that can be used by other tools to support access from other context.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The following IDL code declares a coclass named SomeClass which implements an interface named ISomeInterface.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This is conceptually equivalent to the following C++ code where ISomeInterface is a pure virtual class, a.k.a. abstract base class.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In C++, COM objects are instantiated via the COM subsystem CoCreateInstance function that takes the CLSID and IID.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM object uses reference counting to manage object lifetime.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An object's reference count is controlled by the clients through the `IUnknown` `AddRef` and `Release` methods.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM objects are responsible for freeing their own memory when the reference count drops to zero.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Visual Basic) provide automatic reference counting to simplify object use.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In C++, a smart pointer can be used to automate reference count management.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] For remote objects, not all reference count calls are sent over the wire.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A proxy keeps only one reference on the remote object and maintains its own local reference count.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] To simplify COM development for C++ developers, Microsoft introduced ATL (Active Template Library).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] ATL provides a relatively high-level COM development paradigm.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] It also shields COM client application developers from the need to directly maintain reference counting, by providing smart pointer types.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Other libraries and languages that are COM-aware include the Microsoft Foundation Classes, the VC Compiler COM Support, VBScript, Visual Basic, ECMAScript (JavaScript) and Borland Delphi.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is a language agnostic binary standard that allows objects to be used in any programming context able to access its binary interfaces.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM client software is responsible for enabling the COM sub-system, instantiating and reference-counting COM objects and querying objects for supported interfaces.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The Microsoft Visual C++ compiler supports extensions to the C++ language, referred to as *C++ Attributes*, that are designed to simplify COM development and minimize boilerplate code required to implement COM servers in C++.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Originally, type library metadata was required to be stored in the system registry.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM client would use the registry information for object creation.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Registration-free (RegFree) COM was introduced with Windows XP to allow storing type library metadata as an assembly manifest either as a resource in the executable file or in a separate file installed with the component.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This allows multiple versions of the same component to be installed on the same computer, in different directories.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This technology has limited support for EXE COM servers and cannot be used for system-wide components such as MDAC, MSXML, DirectX or Internet Explorer.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] During application loading, the Windows loader searches for the manifest.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] If it is present, the loader adds information from it to the activation context.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] When the COM class factory tries to instantiate a class, the activation context is first checked to see if an implementation for the CLSID can be found.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Only if the lookup fails, the registry is scanned.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM object can be created without type library information, and instead only a path to the DLL file and CLSID.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A client can use the COM DLL function `DllGetClassObject` with the CLSID and IID_IClassFactory to create an instance of a factory object.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The client can then use the factory object's `CreateInstance` to create an instance.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This is the same process the COM sub-system uses.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] If an object created this way creates another object, it will do so in the usual way (using the registry or manifest).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] But it can create internal objects (which may not be registered at all), and hand out references to interfaces to them, using its own private knowledge.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A COM object can be transparently created and used from within the same process (in-process), across process boundaries (out-of-process), or remotely over the network (DCOM).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Out-of-process and remote objects use marshalling to serialize method calls and return values over process or network boundaries.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This marshalling is invisible to the client, which accesses the object as if it were a local in-process object.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In COM, threading is addressed through a concept known as *apartments*.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] An individual COM object lives in exactly one apartment, which might either be single-threaded or multi-threaded.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] There are three types of apartments in COM: *Single-Threaded Apartment (STA)*, *Multi-Threaded Apartment (MTA)*, and *Thread Neutral Apartment* (NA).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Each apartment represents one mechanism whereby an object's internal state may be synchronized across multiple threads.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] A process can consist of multiple COM objects, some of which may use STA and others of which may use MTA.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] All threads accessing COM objects similarly live in one apartment.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The choice of apartment for COM objects and threads are determined at run-time, and cannot be changed.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Threads and objects which belong to the same apartment follow the same thread access rules.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Method calls which are made inside the same apartment are therefore performed directly without any assistance from COM.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Method calls made across apartments are achieved via marshalling.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This requires the use of proxies and stubs.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] COM is relatively complex especially compared to more modern component technologies such as .NET.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] When an STA is initialized it creates a hidden window that is used for inter-apartment and inter-process message routing.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This window must have its message queue regularly "pumped".
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This construct is known as a "message pump".
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] On earlier versions of Windows, failure to do so could cause system-wide deadlocks.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This problem is complicated by some Windows APIs that initialize COM as part of their implementation, which causes a "leak" of implementation details.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Reference counting within COM may cause problems if two or more objects are circularly referenced.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] The design of an application must take this into account so that objects are not left orphaned.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Objects may also be left with active reference counts if the COM "event sink" model is used.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Since the object that fires the event needs a reference to the object reacting to the event, the latter's reference count will never reach zero.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Reference cycles are typically broken using either out-of-band termination or split identities.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In the out-of-band termination technique, an object exposes a method which, when called, forces it to drop its references to other objects, thereby breaking the cycle.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] In the split identity technique, a single implementation exposes two separate COM objects (also known as identities).
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] This creates a weak reference between the COM objects, preventing a reference cycle.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Because in-process COM components are implemented in DLL files and registration only allows for a single version per CLSID, they might in some situations be subject to the "DLL Hell" effect.
[src:com-automation/component-object-model] Registration-free COM capability eliminates this problem for in-process components; registration-free COM is not available for out-of-process servers.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] The extension COM into Distributed COM was due to extensive use of DCE/RPC (Distributed Computing Environment/Remote Procedure Calls) – more specifically Microsoft's enhanced version, known as MSRPC.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] One of the key factors in solving these problems is the use of DCE/RPC as the underlying RPC mechanism behind DCOM.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] DCE/RPC has strictly defined rules regarding marshalling and who is responsible for freeing memory.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] Proponents of both of these technologies saw them as one day becoming the model for code and service-reuse over the Internet.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] However, the difficulties involved in getting either of these technologies to work over Internet firewalls, and on unknown and insecure machines, meant that normal HTTP requests in combination with web browsers won out over both of them.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] Microsoft, at one point, attempted to remediate these shortcomings by adding an extra HTTP transport to DCE/RPC called *ncacn_http* (Network Computing Architecture connection-oriented protocol).
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] DCOM was publicly launched as a beta for Windows 95 September 18, 1996.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] As part of the initiative that began at Microsoft as part of Secure Development Lifecycle to re-architect insecure code, DCOM saw some significant security-focused changes in Windows XP Service Pack 2.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] In response to a security vulnerability reported by Tencent Security Xuanwu Lab in June 2021, Microsoft released security updates for several versions of Windows and Windows Server, hardening access to DCOM.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] In 1995, Digital and Microsoft announced Affinity for OpenVMS (also known as NT Affinity) which was intended to allow OpenVMS to serve as the persistence layer for Windows NT client-server applications.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] As part of this initiative, an implementation of the Distributed Component Object Model (DCOM) was added to OpenVMS Alpha.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] In order to support DCOM, VMS was provided with implementations of the Windows Registry, NTLM authentication, and a subset of Win32 APIs needed to support COM.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] DCOM was first added to OpenVMS V7.2-1 for the Alpha.
[src:com-automation/distributed-component-object-model] A similar implementation of DCOM was added to Digital Unix as part of the AllConnect program.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] In object-oriented programming, an **interface** or **protocol type** is a data type that acts as an abstraction of a class.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] It describes a set of method signatures, the implementations of which may be provided by multiple classes that are otherwise not necessarily related to each other.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] A class which provides the methods listed in an interface is said to *implement* the interface, or to *adopt* the protocol.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Interfaces are useful for encapsulation and reducing coupling.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] For example, in Java, the `java.lang.Comparable<T>` interface specifies the method `compareTo()`.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Thus, a sorting method only needs to take objects of types which implement `java.lang.Comparable<T>` to sort them, without knowing about the inner nature of the class (except that two of these objects can be compared via `compareTo()`).
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages provide explicit language support for interfaces: Ada, C#, D, Dart, Delphi, Go, Java, Logtalk, Object Pascal, Objective-C, OCaml, PHP, Racket, Swift, Python 3.8.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] In languages supporting multiple inheritance, such as C++, interfaces are abstract classes.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] In languages without explicit support, interfaces are often still present as conventions; this is known as duck typing.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] For example, in Python, any class can implement an `__iter__` method and be used as an iterable.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Classes may also explicitly subclass an ABC, such as `collections.abc.Iterable`.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Type classes in languages like Haskell, or module signatures in ML and OCaml, are used for many of the same things as are interfaces.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] In Rust, interfaces are called *traits*.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] In C++, there are multiple ways to resemble interfaces.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] One such way is the Java-style interface, which is done using abstract classes.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] The other, which resembles Go interfaces, is using concepts.
[src:com-automation/interface-object-oriented-programming] Unlike inheritance, with concepts any type may satisfy a concept (not just classes) so long as it satisfies all of its requirements.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE allows an editing application to export part of a document to another editing application and then import it with additional content.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] For example, a desktop publishing system might send some text to a word processor or a picture to a bitmap editor using OLE.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The main benefit of OLE is to add different kinds of data to a document from different applications, like a text editor and an image editor.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This creates a Compound File Binary Format document and a master file to which the document makes reference.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Changes to data in the master file immediately affect the document that references it.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This is called "linking" (instead of "embedding").
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE can also be used to transfer data between different applications using drag and drop or clipboard operations.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE 1.0, released in 1990, was an evolution of the original Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE) concept that Microsoft developed for earlier versions of Windows.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] While DDE was limited to transferring limited amounts of data between two running applications, OLE was capable of maintaining active links between two documents or even embedding one type of document within another.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE servers and clients communicate with system libraries using virtual function tables, or VTBLs.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The VTBL consists of a structure of function pointers that the system library can use to communicate with the server or client.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The server and client libraries, OLESVR.DLL and OLECLI.DLL, were originally designed to communicate between themselves using the WM_DDE_EXECUTE message.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE 1.0 later evolved to become an architecture for software components known as the Component Object Model (COM), and later DCOM.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] When an OLE object is placed on the clipboard or embedded in a document, both a visual representation in native Windows formats (such as a bitmap or metafile) is stored, as well as the underlying data in its own format.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This allows applications to display the object without loading the application used to create the object, while also allowing the object to be edited, if the appropriate application is installed.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The **Object Packager**, a component of OLE, shipping from Windows 3.1 up to Windows XP allows a non-OLE object to be "packaged" so it can be embedded into an OLE client.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE 2.0 was the next evolution of OLE, sharing many of the same goals as version 1.0, but was re-implemented on top of the COM instead of using VTBLs directly.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] New features were OLE automation, drag-and-drop, in-place activation and structured storage.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Monikers evolved from OLE 1 object names, and provided a hierarchical object and resource naming system similar to URLs or URIs, which were independently invented.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Windows now has merged the two technologies supporting a URL Moniker type, and a Moniker URL scheme.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE 2.0 introduced UUID to label API objects.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE custom controls were introduced in 1994 as a replacement for the now deprecated Visual Basic Extension controls.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Instead of upgrading these, the new architecture was based on OLE.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] In particular, any container that supported OLE 2.0 could already embed OLE custom controls, although these controls cannot react to events unless the container supports this.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE custom controls are usually shipped in the form of a dynamic link library with the .ocx extension.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] In 1996 all interfaces for controls (except IUnknown) were made optional to keep the file size of controls down, so they would download faster; these were then called ActiveX Controls.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OLE objects and containers are implemented on top of the Component Object Model; they are objects that can implement interfaces to export their functionality.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Only the **IOleObject** interface is compulsory, but other interfaces may also need to be implemented if the functionality exported by those interfaces is required.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] To ease understanding of what follows, some terminology has to be explained.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The view status of an object is whether the object is transparent, opaque, or opaque with a solid background, and whether it supports drawing with a specified aspect.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] The site of an object is an object representing the location of the object in its container.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] A container supports a site object for every object contained.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] What follows is a list of interfaces, grouped by the object that usually needs to implement them.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Interfaces usually implemented by the OLE object are usually called on by the OLE container, and vice versa.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Note that in the following list indentation indicates interface inheritance.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] All non-indented interfaces derive from **IUnknown**.
