[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Called by the outermost container of an object to interact with it while it's active, e.g. to process accelerator keys in the container's message queue that are meant for the contained object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Called by the container to activate or deactivate the object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] A windowless object is an object that doesn't have its own window but it instead displayed in its container's window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It is used by the container to relay messages received by the container's window that are intended for the contained object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] For example, if the mouse is moved over a window, Windows places a mouse move message along with the mouse coordinates in the message queue of the window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] If this window contains windowless embedded objects, the message may have to be relayed to such an object if the coordinates of the mouse-pointer are over this object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Allows the object to support linking, e.g. by allowing the container to set the source of a linked object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Arguably the most important interface for an OLE object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] and to execute objects defined as "verbs" on the object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] These verbs often include "Open" or "Edit", but can also include other verbs.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] One of the verbs is defined to be the principal verb, and it is executed when the user double-clicks an object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] and this interface, the underlying implementation is usually shared.
