[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Allows the implementer to receive notifications when the object is saved, closed, or renamed, or when its data or visual presentation changes.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Additionally allows the implementer to receive notifications when the link source of the OLE object changes.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Additionally allows the implementer to receive notifications when the view status of the OLE object changes.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This interface allows the caller to obtain information on the container and location of an object, as well requesting that the object be saved, resized, shown, hidden, et cetera.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Allows the caller to ask for the object on this site to be activated immediately.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This interface allows the caller to enumerate embedded objects in a container, or to find such objects by name.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It is primarily useful if the container wishes to support links to embedded objects.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Enables embedded objects to negotiate space for toolbars on the container's window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Allows the caller to ask the container to insert its menu items in an empty menu that will become the cooperative menu.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Also allows the caller to ask the container to show or hide this menu, to show or hide dialog boxes, and to process accelerator keys received by the contained object intended for the container.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] If a container implements this interface, it allows embedded objects to be activated in place, i.e. without opening in a separate window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] If a container implements this interface, it allows embedded objects to check whether they need to redraw on activation or deactivation.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It also allows them to request their UI to activate.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] If a container wishes to support windowless embedded objects, it needs to provide functionality to embedded objects to replace the functionality normally provided by an embedded object's window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] For example this interface provides a way to access the container's window's device context, thereby enabling the embedded object to draw in the container's window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Contains the methods that the standard OLE dialog boxes that manage linked objects use to update linked objects in a container, or to query and change their sources.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Used by the "Links", "Change source", "Update links" and "Object properties" dialog boxes.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Additionally allows the dialog boxes to query when linked objects were last updated, and whether this was done automatically or manually.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Contains the methods needed by the "Object properties" dialog box.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] For example if the user opens the "Object properties" dialog box and asks for the object to be converted to another type, a method on this interface is called.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Provides a centralized undo service to both the container itself and to embedded objects.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] that pertain to data change notifications can be implemented by calling the methods of this interface.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] that pertain to notifications can be implemented by calling the methods of this interface.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Implemented by objects that can be dragged, i.e. that can be the source of a drag-and-drop operations.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] When implemented it allows the object to draw drag-and-drop effects, and to specify when the object is dropped, or the drag-and-drop operation is cancelled.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Implemented by objects that accept dropped objects, i.e. that can be the target of drag-and-drop operations.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] When implemented it allows the target to specify if a dropped object will be accepted, and what happens to an object after it is dropped.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Can be implemented by objects (OLE objects, OLE containers, and other objects) that wish to support certain standard commands.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It allows callers to query if commands are supported, and to execute commands.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Commands that an object might typically wish to implement may include things like "delete", "cut", "copy", "paste", "undo", "find", "print", "save", "zoom", and so on.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Currently 58 standard commands have been defined, and they include commands commonly used by office software, web browsers and similar applications.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Represents an action that can be undone.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It contains all information necessary to undo an action.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Allows an undo unit to contain other undo units.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] In essence this allows the undo unit to act as an undo stack, grouping undo units together.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] For example, if a macro is run, all undo-able actions performed by the macro may be grouped together in one undo unit.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] This interface represents a window of a container or contained object.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] It allows callers to obtain the handle of the window, and to toggle the context-sensitive help function.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] When the context-sensitive help function is turned on, typically the mouse-pointer changes to an arrow with a question mark to indicate that clicking a user interface element will result in opening a help window.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OpenDoc technology tried to compete with OLE.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Some of Microsoft's competitors considered OpenDoc to be more robust and easier to use.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] OpenDoc allowed users to view and edit information across applications, directly in competition with Microsoft's proprietary OLE standard.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] In 1993 some Microsoft competitors established a consortium called the Component Integration Laboratories ("CIL") to develop OpenDoc as an open standard for cross-platform linking and embedding.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Microsoft required OLE compatibility as a condition of Microsoft's certification of an application's compatibility with Windows 95.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Microsoft initially announced that applications using OpenDoc would be deemed compatible with OLE, and would receive certification for Windows 95.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Microsoft later reversed the decision and said that applications using OpenDoc might not receive certification at all.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] Microsoft withheld specifications and debugged versions of OLE until after it had released its competing applications.
[src:com-automation/object-linking-and-embedding] If software that understands an OLE object is not available, the object is usually replaced by a picture (bitmap representation of the object) or not displayed at all.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] In Microsoft Windows applications programming, **OLE Automation** (later renamed to simply **Automation**) is an inter-process communication mechanism created by Microsoft.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] It is based on a subset of Component Object Model (COM) that was intended for use by scripting languages – originally Visual Basic – but now is used by several languages on Windows.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] All automation objects are required to implement the IDispatch interface.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] It provides an infrastructure whereby applications called *automation controllers* can access and manipulate (i.e. set properties of or call methods on) shared *automation objects* that are exported by other applications.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] It supersedes Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE), an older mechanism for applications to control one another.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] As with DDE, in OLE Automation the automation controller is the "client" and the application exporting the automation objects is the "server".
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Contrary to its name, automation objects do not necessarily use Microsoft OLE, although some Automation objects can be used in OLE environments.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] The confusion has its roots in Microsoft's earlier definition of OLE, which was previously more or less a synonym of COM.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] To ensure interoperability, automation interfaces are limited to use a subset of all COM types.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Specifically, automation interfaces must use SAFEARRAY instead of raw COM arrays.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Automation-compatible COM servers can, however, rely on the in-built OLE marshalling implementation.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] This avoids the need for additional proxy/stub projects for marshalling out-of-process.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Automation was designed with the ease of scripting in mind, so controllers often provide languages such as Visual Basic for Applications to end users, allowing them to control automation objects via scripts.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Automation objects are often written in conventional languages such as C++, where C++ attributes can be used to simplify development, Languages such as Visual Basic and Borland Delphi also provides a convenient syntax for Automation which hides the complexity of the underlying implementation.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] In order to automate an application, the developer of an automation controller must know the object model that is employed by the target application exporting activation objects.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] This requires that the developer of the target application publicly document its object model.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Development of automation controllers without knowledge of the target application's object model is "difficult to impossible".
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Due to these complications, Automation components are usually provided with *type libraries*, which contain metadata about classes, interfaces and other features exposed by an object library.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Interfaces are described in Microsoft Interface Definition Language.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Type libraries can be viewed using various tools, such as the Microsoft OLE/COM Object Viewer (`oleview.exe`, part of the Microsoft Platform SDK) or the Object Browser in Visual Basic (up to version 6) and Visual Studio .NET.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Type libraries are used to generate Proxy pattern/stub code for interoperating between COM and other platforms, such as Microsoft .NET and Java.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] While Java lacks built-in COM support, toolsets like JACOB and jSegue can generate proxy source code (consisting of two parts, a set of Java classes and a C++ source for a Java Native Interface DLL) from type libraries.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Another Java based j-Interop library which enables interoperability with COM components without JNI, using DCOM wire protocol (MSRPC) and works on non-Windows platforms also.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Microsoft has publicly documented the object model of all of the applications in Microsoft Office, and some other software developers have also documented the object models of their applications.
[src:com-automation/ole-automation] Object models are presented to automation controllers as type libraries, with their interfaces described in ODL.
